\begin_layout Section
Comparing demand responses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to a debiasing intervention as carried out by AT, another approach
 to measuring bias from inattention or imperfect information is what we
 have called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

comparing demand responses.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Imagine that consumer type 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

's normative valuation for the CFL relative to the incandescent lightbulb
 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V_{\theta}=v_{\theta}-p+e,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 reflects heterogeneous preferences for the non-price characteristics of
 the two bulbs, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the relative price of the CFL, and 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is the present discounted value of the lifetime relative electricity savings
 from the CFL.
 More precisely, if the average lightbulb will be used 1000 hours per year
 over four years (a rough approximation), the annual discount factor is
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=0.95$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{e}$
\end_inset

 is the marginal electricity price in dollars per kilowatt-hour (kWh), 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 is electricity use (
\begin_inset Formula $w_{inc}=$
\end_inset

 0.06 kWh per hour and 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{CFL}=0.015$
\end_inset

 kWh per hour), and we assume zero discounting, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
e=e(p_{e})=\sum_{t=1}^{4}\delta^{t}\cdot1000\cdot p_{e}\cdot(w_{inc}-w_{CFL})\label{eq:e}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 dollars.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If consumers do not pay full attention to the electricity savings 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

, then type 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

's actual valuation would be
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U=v-p+(1-\tilde{\gamma}_{\theta})e,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}_{\theta}$
\end_inset

 reflects the share of 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 that is misperceived.
 In the standard model, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}_{\theta}=0$
\end_inset

.
 If electricity prices are not fully salient or consumers underestimate
 the electricity savings 
\begin_inset Formula $(w_{inc}-w_{CFL})$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}_{\theta}>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Electricity prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{e}$
\end_inset

 vary across utilities and states.
 A testable hypothesis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}_{\theta}=0$
\end_inset

 is that their valuations will reflect this cross-sectional variation.
 Let's test this hypothesis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
2.1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The file 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "MarginalElectricityPrice.dta"
target "https://github.com/huntallcott/BehavioralPublicProblemSet/blob/master/analysis/input/MarginalElectricityPrice.dta"
literal "false"

\end_inset

